JSON Objects¶

Basic fields¶

All OpenRCT2 JSON Objects contain the following fields:

JSON Object

type: object

  • id*

OpenRCT2 id of the object. This should be formatted as “objectsource.objecttype.objectname” or similar. This value MUST be universally unique.

type: string

  • authors*

Array containing the authors of the object

type: array

examples

 
[
  "spacek531"
]

[
  "Chris Sawyer",
  "Simon Foster"
]

items

The name of (one of) the author(s)

type: string

  • version

Version of the object

type: string

examples

 
"1.0"

  • originalId

For converted objects, this represents the original DAT header. The three sections are the flags, name, and checksum. This shouldn’t be used for new (not converted) objects.

type: string

examples

 
"00000000|RMCT2   |00003000"

"0A188A80|4X4     |0DB8676C"

  • sourceGame

The source(s) of the object. Either a single string or an array containing each source

anyOf

Source String

type: string

enum

rct1, rct1aa, rct1ll, rct2, rct2ww, rct2tt, official, custom

Array of Source Strings

type: array

  • objectType*

The type of the object

type: string

enum

ride, footpath, footpath_banner, footpath_item, scenery_small, scenery_large, scenery_wall, scenery_group, park_entrance, water, terrain_surface, terrain_edge, station, music, footpath_surface, footpath_railings

  • images

The location of images for the object

type: array

examples

 
[
  {
    "path": "images/preview.png",
    "x": 0,
    "y": 0
  }
]

[
  "$RCT2:OBJDATA/TLP.DAT[0..3]"
]

[
  "$G1[5595]",
  "$G1[1663..1746]"
]

items

anyOf

A description of an image.

type: object

  • path

The relative path to a png file.

type: string

  • x

The image’s x-offset.

type: integer

  • y

The image’s y-offset.

type: integer

  • format

If set to “raw”, this image will not be run-length encoded (rare).

type: string

  • keepPalette

If true, OpenRCT2 will assume the png file is already paletted correctly, and will just read the palette indexes without looking at colors.

type: boolean

The source of the image. This can be an indexed ranged into a DAT file (such as G1.DAT or an object .DAT). Otherwise, it can be a relative path to a png file (offsets default to 0,0).

type: string

  • strings

Contains the various strings used for the object

type: object

examples

 
{
  "name": {
    "en-GB": "Single Rail Roller Coaster Trains"
  },
  "description": {
    "en-GB": "Riders ride single file on a narrow monorail track as they race through tight inversions and direction changes"
  },
  "capacity": {
    "en-GB": "1 passenger per car"
  }
}

  • name

Contains the name of the object in all the different supported languages

type: object

  • en-GB

The string in English. Add other entries for other languages

  • description

Contains a short description of the object in all the different supported languages

type: object

  • en-GB

  • capacity

For rides, this contains text describing the capacity in all the different supported languages

type: object

  • en-GB

  • properties

This object contains all the properties of the object. What’s included here depends on what type of object this is.

type: object
